  "prompt": "Are there any British airlines that provide cabin crew accommodation?",
  "response": "Yes, several British airlines provide accommodation for their cabin crew, especially for those who are based away from their home or who are required to stay overnight (layovers) due to their flight schedules. Here are some examples of British airlines that typically offer cabin crew accommodation:\n\n1. **British Airways (BA)**  \n   British Airways often provides accommodation for cabin crew during layovers, especially on international routes. They may also offer accommodation for crew members who are based in cities other than their home location.\n\n2. **Virgin Atlantic**  \n   Virgin Atlantic provides accommodation for cabin crew during layovers and may also assist with accommodation for those relocating to their base locations.\n\n3. **EasyJet**  \n   EasyJet offers accommodation for cabin crew during layovers, particularly for crew based in cities where they do not live locally.\n\n4. **TUI Airways**  \n   TUI Airways often provides accommodation for crew during layovers and may also assist with lodging for those relocating to their base cities.\n\n5. **Jet2**  \n   Jet2 offers accommodation for cabin crew during layovers, especially for international flights.\n\n6. **Ryanair** (UK-based crew)  \n   While Ryanair is an Irish airline, it employs many UK-based crew members and provides accommodation during layovers for its crew.\n\n### Accommodation Details  \n- **Layovers**: Airlines typically book hotels for cabin crew during layovers between flights.  \n- **Relocation Assistance**: Some airlines may provide temporary accommodation for crew relocating to a new base city.  \n- **Base Accommodation**: For crew living away from their permanent residence, some airlines may offer assistance with finding long-term accommodation.\n\nIf you're considering applying to a specific airline, it\u2019s always a good idea to confirm their accommodation policies during the recruitment process, as these can vary depending on the airline and the role.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
